04415nam a22005895i 9780804767675DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047676757 a10.1515/97808047676752doi  a(DE-B1597)582182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPER0040002bisacsh00aLaw on the Screen /ced. by Austin Sarat, Lawrence Douglas, Martha Merrill Umphrey. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Amherst Series in Law, Jurisprudence, and Social Thought00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tContributors -- tOn Film and Law: Broadening the Focus -- tPART I Studies of Representation -- tCinematic Judgment and Jurisprudence: A Woman's Memory, Recovery, and Justice in a Post-Traumatic Society (A Study of Polanski's Death and the Maiden) -- tThe Racial-Spatial Order and the Law: Devil in a Blue Dress -- tAnti-Oedipus, Lynch: Initiatory Rites and the Ordeal of Justice -- tPART II Studies of Reception -- tReproducing a Trial: Evidence and Its Assessment in Paradise Lost -- tA Case for Corrective Criticism: A Civil Action -- t"Everyone Went Wild over It": Film Audiences, Political Cinema, and Mr. Smith Goes to Washington -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe proliferation of images of law, legal processes, and officials on television and in film is a phenomenon of enormous significance. Mass-mediated images are as powerful, pervasive, and important as are other early twenty-first-century social forces—e.g. globalization, neo-colonialism, and human rights—in shaping and transforming legal life. Yet scholars have only recently begun to examine how law works in this new arena and to explore the consequences of the representation of law in the moving image. Law on the Screen advances our understanding of the connection between law and film by analyzing them as narrative forms, examining film for its jurisprudential content—that is, its ways of critiquing the present legal world and imagining an alternative one—and expanding studies of the representation of law in film to include questions of reception.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aCinema and Media Studies. 4aLaw -- Law and Society. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aDouglas, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKamir, Orit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMnookin, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarat, Austin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShapiro, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSherwin, Richard K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmoodin, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWaldman, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476767540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767675/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles